# Booklet Studio frontend and pipeline changes

This document records the Booklet Studio changes included in the accompanying
commit. The work covers the interactive company setup flow, persisted source
recovery, plan-document readiness, live HTML preview behavior, and the final
PDF boundary.

## Intended workflow

Booklet Studio now treats setup as four ordered phases:

1. Employer
2. Plans
3. Rates
4. Notes

A later phase unlocks only when the source-backed requirements for the prior
phase are complete. Uploading a file alone does not mark a phase complete.
Completion is derived from persisted files, classifications, extracted facts,
and the required-plan checklist.

The Notes phase is the final catch-all. It shows every unresolved backend
question regardless of which source first surfaced it, followed by an optional
instructions field for corrections, exclusions, decisions, and preferred
client language.

## Employer source experience

- Uploading the employer application initially shows Document and Extracted
  tabs rather than immediately rendering company-profile forms.
- Extracted stays in a loading state until source-backed facts arrive.
- Document lists stored source files but does not mount an inline preview until
  the user explicitly clicks a file.
- The original source is fetched through an ownership-checked
  `source_download` backend action.
- Users can close a preview, add another source, or delete a source.

## Required plan checklist

- Employer-application facts create the requested-plan checklist.
- The plan uploader is a persistent multi-file drag area above the checklist.
- Uploads are unrestricted by exact document type; supported files can be
  selected or dragged in together.
- Plan identity is reconciled from extracted plan names, classification
  metadata, benefit type, and safe exact filename matching.
- Similar plan names do not satisfy one another, and a generic type-only source
  cannot satisfy several named options.
- Filename matches can show a provisional received/parsing state immediately,
  but they do not complete the phase until backend verification arrives.
- The backend now emits an immediate heuristic classification, a confirmed
  classification per file, and per-file plan parse start/extract/complete
  events.
- Only the checklist row associated with the file being parsed shows a spinner.
  It changes to a checkmark after that file is verified.
- Already-verified classifications are never overwritten by a lower-fidelity
  provisional rerun. Uploading a rate file or an additional source therefore
  cannot temporarily reset green plan checks or force navigation back to Plans.

## Persistence and navigation

- Thread and run IDs remain in the recovery URL.
- The selected phase is persisted in the `phase` query parameter.
- Reload waits for backend thread restoration before enforcing phase locks.
- A saved unlocked phase remains selected after reload; a genuinely locked
  phase safely falls back to the latest available step.
- Existing files are merged with later upload responses instead of being
  replaced by only the newest upload batch.
- Final follow-up questions do not retroactively erase completion of Employer,
  Plans, or Rates. They remain visible in Notes.

## HTML preview and PDF lifecycle

Interactive frontend runs explicitly request `html_preview` output. In that
mode the backend:

- performs classification, extraction, plan/rate matching, outline creation,
  and source-backed HTML rendering;
- publishes each available section artifact as soon as its dependencies are
  ready; and
- returns a preview result without invoking the PDF renderer.

The final PDF run starts only when Employer, Plans, Rates, and all required
follow-up details are complete. PDF preview and download controls remain
disabled until that final run has a real PDF URL and no remaining blockers.

## Live text streaming

- New section artifacts automatically select and scroll to the affected HTML
  page.
- Text appears progressively inside the HTML preview rather than mounting in a
  single paint.
- Each section keeps its own prior HTML baseline.
- Subsequent revisions use a word-level diff and animate only inserted or
  changed words. Stable headings, tables, footers, and earlier copy remain
  visible and do not restart.
- Punctuation-only movement does not cause an unchanged word to replay.
- Concurrent backend extraction is allowed, but frontend text animations are
  serialized through a queue. Exactly one section streams at a time, then the
  preview advances to the next queued section.
- Section-specific baselines and revisions prevent simultaneous extraction
  results from overwriting or diffing against one another.
- Reduced-motion browser preferences disable the word animation.
- Small updates apply immediately: an existing section must change by at least
  four words, and a new section needs at least eight words, before streaming is
  triggered.

## Backend and API contract

- Generation runs have an `outputMode` of `html_preview` or `final_pdf`.
- Run status includes the persisted `preview` state.
- Preview runs skip quality/PDF rendering while retaining HTML section
  artifacts and extraction state.
- Once setup is complete, the frontend promotes the saved preview thread to a
  final PDF run.
- Source downloads verify thread ownership, file attachment, company scope,
  and file ownership before returning stored bytes.
- Fast and confirmed classification events include enough per-file metadata for
  the frontend checklist to update before the overall run completes.

## Primary files

- `src/BookletStudio.jsx`: phase UX, checklist, source tabs, gated navigation,
  Notes catch-all, preview behavior, and PDF controls.
- `src/useBookletStudioBackend.js`: recovery, upload merging, generation mode,
  per-file processing, serialized section stream queue, and finalization.
- `src/bookletStudioReadiness.js`: phase readiness, plan requirements, matching,
  stable classification merging, and setup completion.
- `src/bookletTextStream.js`: visible-text parsing, section-local word diffing,
  animation duration, and streamed HTML generation.
- `src/bookletStudioApi.ts`: source download and output-mode API support.
- `src/bookletStudio.css`: source review, checklist, parsing, missing-item, and
  preview states.
- `api/booklet-pipeline.ts`: secure source download and output-mode validation.
- `lib/booklet-pipeline.ts`: fast classification events, per-file parse events,
  HTML-only pipeline results, and final-PDF control.
- `lib/booklet-run-service.ts`, `lib/booklet-thread-store.ts`, and
  `lib/booklet-types.ts`: preview execution and persisted run contract.

## Verification

The focused test coverage includes:

- HTML preview runs never invoking the PDF renderer;
- output mode persistence;
- source file merging;
- phase restoration and source-backed readiness;
- exact and type-aware plan reconciliation;
- protection against similar-plan cross-matches;
- provisional filename receipt and per-file parsing states;
- preservation of verified plan classifications during later provisional runs;
- whole-page initial text streaming;
- changed-word-only section updates; and
- independent concurrent section diffs.

Final yes/no blockers are removed as soon as either answer is saved. The
answer is persisted before regeneration, resolved boolean blockers cannot
reappear during the next pipeline pass, and answering the last blocker allows
the automatic final-PDF run to expose the download action.

The production Vite build and `git diff --check` are run before deployment.
